- var pagetype = "styleguide"
- var page = "Typography"

doctype html
html(lang="en")
  head
    include ./layout/_head.jade
  body(class='#{pagetype}')
    header.styleguide-header
      include ./layout/_navbar.jade
      
    main.styleguide-container(role='main')

      .container
        .row
          .col.s12.m9.l10

            .section
              h2.header Montserrat
              p.caption The standard font Drupal social uses is Montserrat. We have included the font files with our framework.
              p We bundle our framework with 3 different font weights you can use: 300, 500 and 700
              ul.list
                li.h4(style='font-weight:300') Font with weight 300 
                li.h4(style='font-weight:500') Font with weight 500 
                li.h4(style='font-weight:700') Font with weight 700

            .section
              h4 Removing default font
              p In case you don't want to use Montserrat on your webpage, fear not. Simply change the font stack by modifying the code below to your liking and add it to your custom css.
              pre      
                code.language-css.
                  html {
                    font-family: 'montserrat', sans-serif;
                  }
                    
            .section
              h2.header Headers
              
              p 
                :markdown
                  We provide some basic styling on header tags. In the example, you can see the the 6 header tags' different sizes. In the `_default.scss` you can define the heading sizes per breakpoint.
              
              .card-panel
                h1 Heading h1
                h2 Heading h2
                h3 Heading h3
                h4 Heading h4
                h5 Heading h5
                h6 Heading h6
            .section
              h2.header Blockquotes
              p Blockquotes are mainly used to give emphasis to a quote or citation. You can also use these for some extra text hierarchy and emphasis.
              blockquote
                | This is an example quotation that uses the blockquote tag.
                br
                | Here is another line to make it look bigger.

              pre      
                code.language-markup.
                  <blockquote>
                    This is an example quotation that uses the blockquote tag.
                  </blockquote>
            
            .section
              h2.header Flow text
              #flow-text-demo.card-panel
                p.flow-text
                  :markdown
                    Create automagical fluid typography with a new `responsive` property on `font-size`. 
                p.flow-text
                  :markdown
                    To see Flow Text in action, slowly resize your browser and watch the size of this text body change! Use the button above to toggle off/on flow-text to see the difference!
              a#flow-toggle.btn.waves-effect.waves-light Toggle flow-text
              br
              br
              p To use flow-text on a body of text, simply just add the class `flow-text` to a tag, see the code blow.
              pre      
                code.language-markup.
                  <p class="flow-text">I am Flow Text</p>
            .section
              h4 Specifying parameters
              p
                :markdown
                  Youâ€™ll probably want to change those defaults and have some control over the bounds of a font size. The best way to do this is with a new shorthand syntax in `font-size`, and a new property called `font-range`. Font range specifies the viewport widths between which the font size is fluid, outside of this range the font sizes are set to min/max values.
              p The format of each property is very simple
              pre      
                code.language-css.
                  font-size: responsive [min-font-size] [max-font-size]
                  font-range: [lower-bound] [upper-bound]
              p For example
              pre      
                code.language-css.
                  .flow-text {
                    font-size: responsive 12px 21px;
                    font-range: 420px 1280px;
                  }
                  
              h5 Output
              p Flow text outputs complex calc and vw based font-sizes, along with media queries to set the range between which a font size is fluid.
              pre
                code.language-css.
                
                  html {
                    font-size: calc(12px + 9 * ( (100vw - 420px) / 860));
                  }

                  @media screen and (max-width: 420px) {
                    html {
                      font-size: 12px;
                    }
                  }

                  @media screen and (min-width: 1280px) {
                    html {
                      font-size: 21px;
                    }
                  }
                  
              p With the calc expression above being equivalent to
              pre
                code.language-css.
                  min-size + (min-size - max-size) * ( (100vw - min-width) / ( max-width - min-width) )

  
    include ./layout/_scripts.jade
